= Chapter 3: The Heartbeat of the Warden 
\
Within hours, Valen’s workshop was no longer a secret. The High Council of Inventors—a distinguished group of elder citizens, some wearing the long robes of scholars and others wearing the heavy aprons of master blacksmiths—crowded into the room.

They poked, prodded, and measured the swirling blue portal. But mostly, they marveled at the Echo Crystal.

"It doesn’t just store sound," muttered Master Elian, the city’s chief engineer, adjusting a pair of copper magnifying goggles. "It translates vibrations into pure, usable energy. Valen, my boy... you haven't just found a new world. You’ve found the missing piece of our greatest project."

Elian pointed out the window toward the courtyard, where the massive, four-block-tall stone Warden automaton stood waiting.

"We built the Wardens to protect our deepest mining tunnels from cave spiders and zombies," Elian explained, his voice buzzing with excitement. "But redstone wiring is too slow for a machine that size. It needs a heart. It needs to react instantly. This crystal... this could be its soul."

Valen’s eyes lit up. "Can I help install it, Master?"

"You earned the right," Elian smiled, clapping a hand on Valen’s shoulder.

The entire city gathered in the Central Innovation Courtyard to watch. Hundreds of citizens lined the deepslate balconies, their blue soul lanterns casting a dramatic light over the crowd.

Valen climbed a tall wooden scaffolding until he was eye-to-eye with the giant stone protector. Up close, the Warden looked magnificent. Its body was carved from pristine, reinforced deepslate, and its chest features resembled an open rib cage made of smooth white bone-stone, designed to protect its inner mechanisms.

With careful hands, Valen opened a small latch in the center of the Warden's chest. Inside was a hollow chamber lined with golden redstone wires.

Valen took the pulsing teal Echo Crystal and placed it gently into the slot.

CLICK.

The golden wires immediately snapped into place around the crystal. For a long, tense second, nothing happened. The crowd held its breath.

Then, a deep, resonant THUM-THUM echoed from the machine's chest.

The Echo Crystal began to glow brighter, its teal light bleeding through the rib-like bars of the Warden's chest armor. The energy surged upward. Two long, tendril-like stone antenna on top of the Warden’s head suddenly perked up, twitching back and forth.

The Warden shifted its weight, its massive stone feet grinding against the cobblestone. It raised its head. It didn’t have eyes, but as Valen accidentally dropped his small iron wrench, the Warden’s head snapped instantly toward the sound.

The crowd gasped.

The Warden didn't attack. Instead, sensing no danger, it bowed its massive head respectfully to Valen, its internal crystal humming a peaceful, melodic tune. It was a perfect protector—strong, alert, and entirely loyal to the citizens of Luminos-Vara.

The courtyard erupted into cheers! People clapped and shouted Valen's name.

Later that evening, the High Council called a grand meeting. The success of the Warden proved that they needed more Echo Crystals.

"Valen’s small workshop portal is too dangerous and narrow for transport," the Council Leader announced, gesturing to a massive blueprint on the wall. "We will build a grand gateway right here in the center of the city. A massive, monumental frame that will link directly to the grand Void Temple Valen discovered. We will bring prosperity to Luminos-Vara!"

The citizens cheered, already grabbing their pickaxes and deepslate blocks to begin construction on the giant central portal structure.

Valen smiled, feeling proud. But as he walked back to his workshop to gather his blueprints, a strange sensation washed over him. The deeper he got into the lower tunnels, the quieter it felt. The usual comforting echo of the city felt... muffled.

He unlocked his workshop door and stepped inside.

The small portal was still thrumming, but the ink-black smudge he hadn't noticed earlier had grown. It now covered the entire bottom corner of the portal frame and was creeping across the floor. It looked like a dark, fuzzy carpet of veins, pulsing in perfect, silent rhythm with the portal.

Valen frowned, walking over to it. He reached down to touch the strange, dark moss.

The moment his fingers neared the substance, a soft, chilling whisper echoed in his mind—a sound like a thousand distant voices clicking their tongues in the dark.

Valen pulled his hand back, his heart racing. He shook his head, forcing a laugh. "I'm just tired," he whispered to the empty room. "Too much excitement for one day."

He turned off his lanterns and left, locking the door behind him. Inside the dark room, the creeping black veins—the very first patch of Skulk—slowly stretched out another inch, listening to the retreating sound of his footsteps.